personal name and the name of three kings of Scotland, including Robert the Bruce (1274–1329).","Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Robertsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Robert  .","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish <b>Robertsen</b>, a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Roberson","meanings":["English: variant of   Robertson  ."]},{"name":"Robert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Gilles, Normand, Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Michel, Edouard, Gaston, Yves.","French, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":28,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":37,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":48,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":50,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":64,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":66,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes ROBERTSON was born in 1521, in Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England. She married William BALLARD in 1540, in Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died about 1605, in Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 85, and was buried in Essex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt. 1521–Abt. 1605":"1521–umbes 1605","1518–1605":"1518–1605","1541–1589":"1541–1589","1521–1605":"1521–1605","1571":"1571","Abt. 1605":"umbes 1605","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1589":"1589","1587":"1587","1521":"1521","1585":"1585","1541":"1541","Abt. 1521":"1521","23 Jun 1589":"23. juuni 1589","Abt. 1541":"1541","17 May 1605":"17. mai 1605","Abt. 1540":"1540","1518":"1518","1605":"1605","1549":"1549","Southwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Southwell, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England":"Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Middleton Cheney, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt. 1521–Abt. 1605":"1521–noin 1605","1518–1605":"1518–1605","1541–1589":"1541–1589","1521–1605":"1521–1605","1571":"1571","Abt. 1605":"noin 1605","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1589":"1589","1587":"1587","1521":"1521","1585":"1585","1541":"1541","Abt. 1521":"1521","23 Jun 1589":"23. kesäkuuta 1589","Abt. 1541":"1541","17 May 1605":"17. t